<h2 id="from-waterfall-to-lean--bruce-eckfeld-dev-team-consultant">From Waterfall to Lean â€” Bruce Eckfeld, Dev team consultant</h2>

<p>There are 2 different types of software development:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Predictive â€“ Where you know all of the specs so can go waterfall. (like building a house)</li>
  <li>Adaptive â€“ Where there are a lot of unknowns and things are going to change. (like startups)</li>
</ul>

<p>There are 2 different causes of disruption and waste to your dev cycle:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Common â€“ Things like bad process within your dev team.</li>
  <li>Special â€“ Things like your CEO coming in and changing things mid dev cycle.</li>
</ul>

<p>You need to make sure youâ€™re focused on fixing the right waste. The one thatâ€™ll have the biggest impact in value when fixed.</p>

<h2 id="lean-product-management--melissa-perri-conductor">Lean Product Management â€” Melissa Perri, Conductor</h2>

<p>â€œThis isnâ€™t what I neededâ€ really isnâ€™t what you want to hear from your customers after youâ€™ve built something.</p>

<p><strong>Customers will only use a product if it fills a need</strong>.</p>

<p>Donâ€™t build all of the things. You CANâ€™T built all of the features. You should be pushing back on the vast majority of them. Also you HAVE to validate before building.</p>

<p>Melissa used a formula to work out the amount of $ that it would have cost to built a feature that didnâ€™t work, and shows that to people when she proves that it wouldnâ€™t have worked. She uses costs by working it out using developer salaries, then can compare this to profit made directly from the feature too.</p>

<p>This talk emphasized that bossâ€™s, business, etc really are focused on building stuff. Shipping stuff. Rather than shipping stuff thatâ€™s validated to work.</p>

<p>MVPs are just a test, not a feature. It should never be left up. If youâ€™re building an MVP out enough to be left up then youâ€™re building an MVP wrong. It should be much more minimal.</p>

<h2 id="lean-startup-in-design-consulting--johanna-kollman-sidekick">Lean Startup in Design Consulting â€” Johanna Kollman, Sidekick</h2>

<p>Sprints are good if you know what youâ€™re making. Experiments are needed if you donâ€™t know what youâ€™re making.</p>

